SENTENCE now ,  many people consider john watson to be the founder of behaviorism .
SENTENCE and like other behaviorists ,  he believed that psychologists should study only the behaviors they can observe and measure .
SENTENCE they're not interested in mental processes .
SENTENCE while a person could describe his thoughts ,  no one else can see or hear them to verify the accuracy of his report .
SENTENCE but one thing you can observe is muscular habits .
SENTENCE what watson did was to observe muscular habits because he viewed them as a manifestation of thinking .
SENTENCE one kind of habits that he studied are laryngeal habits .
SENTENCE watson thought laryngeal habits  .
SENTENCE you know ,  from larynx ,  in other words ,  related to the voice box  .
SENTENCE he thought those habits were an expression of thinking .
SENTENCE he argued that for very young children ,  thinking is really talking out loud to oneself because they talk out loud even if they're not trying to communicate with someone in particular .
SENTENCE as the individual matures ,  that overt talking to oneself becomes covert talking to oneself ,  but thinking still shows up as a laryngeal habit .
SENTENCE one of the bits of evidence that supports this is that when people are trying to solve a problem ,  they ,  um ,  typically have increased muscular activity in the throat region .
SENTENCE that is ,  if you put electrodes on the throat and measure muscle potential muscle activity you discover that when people are thinking ,  like if they're diligently trying to solve a problem ,  that there is muscular activity in the throat region .
SENTENCE so ,  watson made the argument that problem solving ,  or thinking ,  can be defined as a set of behaviors a set of responses and in this case the response he observed was the throat activity .
SENTENCE that's what he means when he calls it a laryngeal habit .
SENTENCE now ,  as i am thinking about what i am going to be saying ,  my muscles in my throat are responding .
